<h1 class="hero-h">An AI usage policy <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">your team will actually read.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">Most AI policies are 14 pages of risk-team prose nobody reads. This is a one-page policy framework built for B2B companies between $5M and $50M — the kind that fits on a poster, gets adopted, and still covers the things that matter.</p>
</div></div>

<div style="background:#0A1A0A;border-top:1px solid #1A3A1A;border-bottom:1px solid #1A3A1A;padding:1.25rem 2.5rem;">
<div style="max-width:880px;margin:0 auto;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;font-size:0.78rem;color:#8FAF8F;">
<div>By <a href="/about" style="color:#F0FFF0;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Bill Colbert</a> · <span style="color:#4A6A4A;">Founder, Treetop Growth Strategy</span></div>
<div style="color:#4A6A4A;">Published May 2026 · <a href="/content-library" style="color:#8FAF8F;text-decoration:none;">More from the library</a></div>
</div>
</div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Use this template</span><h2 class="h2">Customize and ship in one afternoon</h2><p class="body">Copy the seven sections below into your own document. Replace the bracketed examples with your actual tools, owners, and data categories. Get the document under one page.</p><div class="callout"><p>The single best predictor that an AI policy will be followed: it fits on one page. The second best: it names a specific human to ask when in doubt. Almost nothing else matters.</p></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Section 1</span><h2 class="h2">Purpose &amp; scope</h2><p class="body"><strong>Sample text:</strong> This policy covers how [Company] employees and contractors may use AI tools (including Claude, ChatGPT, Copilot, Gemini, and similar) in the course of their work. It applies to anyone with a [Company] email address. Questions about anything not covered here go to [Name, Title].</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Section 2</span><h2 class="h2">Approved tools</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Primary:</strong> [Claude Team / ChatGPT Team / etc.]. Provisioned by IT; all employees get a seat.</li><li><strong>Secondary, with approval:</strong> [tool], [tool] — request access from [Name].</li><li><strong>Not approved:</strong> free public versions of any AI tool for work involving customer, employee, or financial data. Personal accounts must not be used for [Company] data.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Section 3</span><h2 class="h2">Data classifications</h2><div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Category</th><th>Examples</th><th>OK in approved AI tools?</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Public</td><td>Marketing copy, published content, public regulatory filings</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Internal</td><td>Process docs, internal memos, training material</td><td>Yes, with approved tools only</td></tr><tr><td>Confidential</td><td>Customer data, contracts, financial detail</td><td>Yes, only in enterprise-tier tools with no-training settings confirmed</td></tr><tr><td>Regulated</td><td>PHI, payment card data, attorney-client privileged content</td><td>Only via tools and configurations explicitly approved for that data class</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Section 4</span><h2 class="h2">What you must do</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Review AI output before using it.</strong> You are responsible for what you ship, not the tool.</li><li><strong>Cite or disclose AI assistance</strong> when (a) a client asks, (b) you are submitting work to a regulated authority, or (c) the work is published under your individual byline.</li><li><strong>Use the approved enterprise tools</strong> when working with any data not classified Public.</li><li><strong>Tell [Name] if you see a useful new pattern</strong> — we want to share it.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Section 5</span><h2 class="h2">What you must not do</h2><ul class="ul"><li>Paste customer data, contracts, or financial detail into free public AI tools.</li><li>Use AI to produce work you cannot or do not review before delivering.</li><li>Use AI to generate fake quotes, fake citations, or fake evidence.</li><li>Make hiring, firing, performance review, or credit decisions based on AI output alone.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Section 6</span><h2 class="h2">When to escalate</h2><p class="body"><strong>Sample text:</strong> If you are unsure whether something fits this policy, ask [Name, Title] before doing it. There is no penalty for asking. There is a penalty for assuming.</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Section 7</span><h2 class="h2">Review</h2><p class="body"><strong>Sample text:</strong> This policy is reviewed every 6 months by [Name] and [Name]. Material changes are communicated in the [weekly all-hands]. The current version always lives at [link].</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Common additions</span><h2 class="h2">Optional sections by industry</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> add an explicit BAA-required section. List the specific platforms covered by your BAA.</li><li><strong>Legal:</strong> add a privileged-information section and a courtesy-disclosure rule for AI-assisted drafts.</li><li><strong>Financial services:</strong> add a section pointing to your firm's existing model risk and disclosure policies.</li><li><strong>Public sector / government contracting:</strong> add a section on whether AI use must be disclosed in deliverables under contract terms.</li></ul></div></section>

